ic drum pages backing store 12-inch mm diameter drum initially known magnetic wheel contained series parallel magnetic tracks around its surface each with its own read/write head each track held bits corresponding two pages 2×32×40 bits one revolution drum took milliseconds during which time both pages could be transferred crt main memory although actual data transfer time depended on latency time took for page arrive under read/write head writing pages drum took about twice long reading drum's rotational speed was synchronised main central processor clock which allowed for additional drums be added data was recorded onto drum using phase modulation technique still known today manchester coding machine's instruction set was increased from ssem initially including multiplication done hardware this increased instructions final specification version ten bits each word were allocated hold instruction code standard instruction time was milliseconds but multiplication was much slower depending on size operand machine's most significant innovation generally considered be its incorporation index registers commonplace on modern computers ssem had included two registers implemented williams tubes accumulator program counter c c had already been assigned tube holding two index registers originally known b-lines was given name b contents registers could be used modify program instructions allowing convenient iteration through array numbers stored memory mark also had fourth tube m hold multiplicand multiplier for multiplication operation programming section punched tape showing how one 40-bit word was encoded eight 5-bit characters bits allocated for each program instruction were used hold instruction code which allowed for different instructions machine had initially increasing when function codes programmatically control data transfer between magnetic drum cathode ray tube crt main store were added on intermediary version programs were input by key switches output was display